The bid submitted by ICC General Contractors, Inc. must be considered non-responsive because it failed to list a duly licensed subcontractor for its Asphalt Paving subcontract work.  
 
Reference California Business and Professions Code Chapter 9, section 7000 et seq. which requires that all contractors hold a valid license at the time that bids are submitted and Section 00 21 13 – Instructions to Bidders of the bid documents which states in part:
 
No Bid Proposal will be considered from a Bidder who, at the time Bid Proposals are
opened, is not licensed to perform the Work of the Contract Documents, in accordance
with the Contractors License Law, California Business & Professions Code §§7000 et
seq.  This requirement is not a mere formality and will not be waived by the District or
its Board of Trustees.  
 
Therefore, the apparent lowest responsive and responsible bidder is Calstate Construction, Inc.. (Calstate).  However, Calstate did not submit its signed Appendix A and Appendix C of the Project Stabilization Agreement (PSA) between the District and the Santa Clara and San Benito Counties Building Trades Council with its bid. The signed PSA documents were submitted to the Purchasing Services office prior to the end of bid opening day on March 5, 2015. 
 
Purchasing Services previously consulted with District’s legal counsel, Mr. Phillip Jaret, regarding the failure of a Contractor to include the requisite signed PSA documents with its bid.  Mr. Jaret concluded that the failure to submit the required PSA documents is a minor irregularity that can and should be waived by the District if the Contractor later cured such deficiency shortly thereafter.  The failure not to provide the PSA documents with its bid does not provide a Contractor with any competitive advantage over the other bidders.  
 
Calstate has completed several public works projects for the District including the Elevator Repairs at both campuses, G Building renovation project and the DOB Swing Space project.  Calstate and its listed subcontractors have each signed the “Agreement To Be Bound” and the “Agreement of Contractors” of the Project Stabilization/Construction Careers Agreement between the District and the Santa Clara & San Benito Counties Building and Construction Trades Council.  
 
The bid price of $246,500 as submitted by Calstate Construction will be funded by  Measure C project #218.
	 
